## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread exceeding a time limit, with `ThreadAbortException` + `ResetAbort` to handle the abort. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed

| Before (.NET Framework)                | After (.NET 8)                              |
|----------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()`   | `Task.Run(work, token)`                     |
| `thread.Join(timeout)`                 | `task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult()` |
| `thread.Abort()`                       | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` — automatic |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)`         | `catch (OperationCanceledException)`        |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()`                  | Removed — not needed                        |

### ⚠️ Key Pitfalls

1. **Work won't stop automatically.** The `Func<T>` delegate doesn't receive the token, so it keeps running in the background after timeout. If `work` is CPU-bound or blocking, it finishes silently. To actually stop work, change the signature:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Callers must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

2. **Don't forget `using`** — `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer leaks.

3. **`Thread.Sleep` won't respond to cancellation.** Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` inside work delegates.

4. **Cooperative ≠ immediate.** Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation only fires at checkpoints (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`). Space them based on acceptable latency.

The second signature (`Func<CancellationToken, T>`) is strongly recommended — without it, timed-out work silently runs to completion, wasting resources.
